Digital Training Curriculum Design for SGO Preventive Health Visit Volunteers\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 Singapore's Silver Generation Office has engaged over 
\f0\b 600,000 seniors
\f1\b0  through its 6,000+ volunteer ambassadors, making effective volunteer preparation essential for this critical public health initiative. This research compiles evidence-based frameworks, practical protocols, and microlearning design principles to structure a 5-module mobile training curriculum that equips volunteers for successful Preventive Health Visits.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 Understanding the SGO volunteer context\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 The Silver Generation Office, established in 2014 as the Pioneer Generation Office and merged with the Agency for Integrated Care in 2018, deploys Silver Generation Ambassadors (SGAs) to conduct door-to-door home visits with seniors aged 60 and above. These Preventive Health Visits can last up to 
\f0\b 45 minutes
\f1\b0  and occur at least once every 18 months per household. Volunteers require a minimum of 
\f0\b 15 hours of training
\f1\b0  covering policy knowledge, soft skills, and practical engagement sessions.\
SGO currently uses the 
\f0\b BELIEF framework
\f1\b0  for engagement training: Break ice, Explore situation, Listen with empathy, Inform to educate, Evaluate and assure, Follow-up. This framework, combined with the Transtheoretical Model of health behavioral changes, guides how volunteers approach conversations about health-seeking behaviors and government schemes.\
The volunteer role encompasses explaining complex government schemes including the Pioneer Generation Package (serving approximately 300,000 seniors born before 1950), the Merdeka Generation Package (approximately 500,000 born 1950-1959), CHAS subsidies, CareShield Life, and newer initiatives like the Majulah Package. Volunteers also conduct basic needs assessments using the Community Screener tool, identify at-risk seniors for follow-up, and support Healthier SG enrollment\'97all while maintaining clear boundaries between their supportive role and medical advice.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 Module 1: Foundations of senior engagement\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 The first module should establish volunteer identity, organizational context, and foundational communication skills essential for building trust with seniors.\

\f0\b Core content areas for 5-7 bite-sized lessons:
\f1\b0 \
SGO mission and the volunteer's role in Age Well SG requires volunteers to understand their contribution to Singapore's broader healthy aging strategy. The curriculum should explain how SGO connects to the 214 Active Ageing Centres island-wide and the coordinated care vision of "one contact point, one assessment, one care plan" being implemented by 2026.\
Understanding aging fundamentals provides essential context. Volunteers must recognize that physical changes affect how seniors process information\'97slower information processing, hearing and vision decline, and need for additional response time. The first signs of physical disorders often manifest as behavioral, mental, or emotional changes rather than obvious physical symptoms. Training should cover the 
\f0\b Geriatric 5Ms framework
\f1\b0 : Mind (cognitive health), Mobility (fall risk), Medications (polypharmacy awareness), Matters Most (patient priorities), and Multicomplexity (social determinants).\
Cultural competency for Singapore's multiethnic context deserves significant attention. Approximately 
\f0\b 41% of Chinese Singaporeans speak Hokkien
\f1\b0  as their primary dialect, with Teochew (21%) and Cantonese (15%) also common among Pioneer and Merdeka generations. Many elderly speak dialects rather than Mandarin despite language policies. Training should cover basic greeting phrases across languages, cultural norms around indirect communication and face-saving, family dynamics emphasizing filial piety, and appropriate use of honorifics (Pakcik/Makcik for Malays, Uncle/Aunty across cultures).\
Active listening forms the communication foundation. The 
\f0\b LISTEN framework
\f1\b0  provides a teachable structure: Look directly at the senior, Involve yourself fully, Show interest through nodding, Take time without rushing, Echo back key points, Note non-verbal cues. Research indicates volunteers should allow 
\f0\b triple the normal response time
\f1\b0  when conversing with elderly, avoid asking multiple questions sequentially, and accept silence as normal.\

\f0\b Scenario practice:
\f1\b0  A branching scenario featuring first contact with a dialect-speaking senior who appears suspicious of the visit, requiring learners to demonstrate appropriate greetings, patience, and rapport-building techniques.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

