\f0\b \cf0 Observational health assessment techniques
\f1\b0  form the practical core. Visual cues of decline include unkempt appearance, inappropriate dress for weather, unexplained bruises, shuffling gait, flat expression, and withdrawal. Signs of malnutrition include 
\f0\b BMI below 22 kg/m\'b2
\f1\b0 , involuntary weight loss exceeding 5% over one month, loose clothing, sunken cheeks, empty refrigerator, and expired food. Cognitive decline warning signs encompass memory loss affecting daily activities, difficulty performing familiar tasks, word-finding problems, disorientation to time/place, poor judgment, misplacing things frequently, and personality changes.\

\f0\b Validated screening tools appropriate for community volunteers
\f1\b0  include:\
The 
\f0\b Katz Index of Independence in ADLs
\f1\b0  assesses six basic functions (bathing, dressing, toileting, transferring, continence, feeding) with scores from 0-6, where 6 indicates independence. Administration takes 5-10 minutes.\
The 
\f0\b DETERMINE Checklist
\f1\b0  for nutrition screening uses ten yes/no questions covering Disease, Eating poorly, Tooth loss, Economic hardship, Reduced social contact, Multiple medicines, Involuntary weight change, Needs assistance, and Elder years. Scores of 6+ indicate high nutritional risk.\
The 
\f0\b 3-Key STEADI Questions
\f1\b0  for fall risk require yes to any of: "Have you fallen in the past year?", "Do you feel unsteady when standing or walking?", or "Do you worry about falling?"\
The 
\f0\b PHQ-2
\f1\b0  depression screening asks about frequency over two weeks of "little interest or pleasure in doing things" and "feeling down, depressed, or hopeless," with scores of 3 or higher suggesting need for further evaluation.\

\f0\b Home environment safety observations
\f1\b0  should follow CDC's Check for Safety checklist: floors (clutter, throw rugs, cords), stairs (handrails, lighting), bathroom (grab bars, non-slip mats), bedroom (clear path to bathroom), lighting adequacy, and emergency phone accessibility.\

\f0\b Escalation protocols require clear categorization:
\f1\b0 \
Immediate escalation (call 995): chest pain, difficulty breathing, stroke symptoms (FAST: Face drooping, Arm weakness, Speech difficulty, Time to call), unresponsiveness, active bleeding, active suicidal ideation with plan.\
Urgent referral (same/next day): falls with injury, sudden confusion, severe dehydration, medication errors discovered, evidence of abuse/neglect, severe depression symptoms, unsafe living conditions.\
Routine referral (1-2 weeks): gradual functional decline, unexplained weight loss, mild depression symptoms, social isolation, medication management concerns, vision/hearing concerns.\

\f0\b Scenario practice:
\f1\b0  An interactive home visit where learners observe the environment and senior's presentation, identify concerns, determine appropriate screening questions, and classify observations into escalation categories.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 Module 3: Communication skills for challenging situations\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 This module develops advanced communication techniques for seniors with specific challenges and teaches motivational interviewing basics for encouraging health-seeking behavior.\

\f0\b Communicating with hearing loss
\f1\b0  requires specific adaptations: get attention before speaking, reduce background noise, position yourself in good lighting with face visible, speak clearly at moderate pace without shouting, don't exaggerate mouth movements, keep hands away from face, use shorter sentences, announce topic changes, and write down key information (dates, names, numbers). If not understood, first repeat exact words, then rephrase differently.\

\f0\b Communicating with cognitively impaired seniors
\f1\b0  follows different principles. Core guidance includes: don't argue or reason, don't remind them they forget things, don't take things personally, do accept blame when something's wrong, and practice 100% forgiveness. Practical techniques vary by stage\'97early dementia requires one question at a time and choices rather than open questions; moderate dementia needs yes/no questions, slow speech, and ample response time; late stages rely on non-verbal communication, touch, and responding to emotions rather than words.\

\f0\b Motivational Interviewing using OARS
\f1\b0  provides a framework volunteers can learn:\

\f0\b Open questions
\f1\b0  invite sharing: instead of "Did you take your medication?" ask "Tell me about how you've been managing your medications." Instead of "Are you lonely?" ask "How have you been spending your days lately?"\

\f0\b Affirmations
\f1\b0  recognize strengths: "I appreciate you being so honest with me today," "Despite everything, you've kept your home so well," "It takes courage to talk about these things."\

\f0\b Reflective listening
\f1\b0  mirrors understanding: When a senior says "I don't see the point of going for checkups anymore at my age," respond with "It sounds like you're wondering if these medical visits are really worth the effort for you."\

\f0\b Summarizing
\f1\b0  confirms understanding: "Let me see if I understand. You're interested in staying healthy, but transportation makes appointments difficult, and you're not sure the doctors really listen. Did I get that right?"\

\f0\b The Readiness Ruler technique
\f1\b0  helps explore motivation: "On a scale of 1 to 10, how ready do you feel to [specific behavior]?" Follow with "Why did you choose that number and not a lower one?" (builds confidence) and "What would it take to move one point higher?"\

\f0\b Addressing resistance and skepticism
\f1\b0  requires understanding common reasons: past negative experiences with bureaucracy, distrust of government motives, fear of losing autonomy, cultural mistrust of institutions, misinformation from peers, and pride about appearing needy. Trust-building strategies include establishing personal connection first, being transparent about your role, demonstrating both competence and warmth, honoring every commitment, and acknowledging their expertise about their own lives.\

\f0\b Managing rejection gracefully
\f1\b0  uses specific scripts: "I completely understand. This is your decision to make. If you ever change your mind, please don't hesitate to contact us. Even if you're not interested in this program, is there anything else I can help with today?"\

\f0\b Sensitive conversation guidance
\f1\b0  for end-of-life planning, memory concerns, financial difficulties, and depression should use the 
\f0\b COMFORT framework
\f1\b0 : Context (appropriate time/private setting), Opening (ask permission), Mindful (aware of emotional state), Follow their lead, Offer support, Respect choices, Time (don't rush).\

\f0\b Scenario practice:
\f1\b0  A branching scenario featuring a resistant senior who initially refuses help, requiring learners to demonstrate motivational interviewing techniques, respect autonomy, and leave the door open for future engagement.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 Module 4: Government schemes and referral pathways\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 This module builds comprehensive knowledge of Singapore's senior support ecosystem, enabling volunteers to explain complex schemes simply and navigate referral pathways effectively.\

\f0\b Pioneer Generation Package
\f1\b0  serves Singaporeans born on or before 31 December 1949 who became citizens by 31 December 1986. Benefits include annual MediSave top-ups of 
\f0\b $300-$1,400
\f1\b0  depending on birth year, MediShield Life premium subsidies of 40-60%, additional 50% off remaining bills at polyclinics and public specialist outpatient clinics, special CHAS clinic subsidies, and the Pioneer Generation Disability Assistance Scheme providing $100/month for those needing help with 3+ Activities of Daily Living.\

\f0\b Merdeka Generation Package
\f1\b0  serves those born 1950-1959 who became citizens by 31 December 1996. Benefits include annual MediSave top-ups of $200-$250, additional 25% off remaining polyclinic/SOC bills, MediShield Life premium subsidies of 5-10% depending on age, one-time $100 PAssion Silver Card top-up, and CareShield Life incentives.\

\f0\b Community Health Assist Scheme (CHAS)
\f1\b0  provides subsidies based on card tier. Blue card (household monthly income per person \uc0\u8804 $1,500 or Annual Value \u8804 $21,000) offers up to $18.50 per visit for common illnesses and $80-$125 for chronic conditions. Orange card (income $1,501-$2,300 or AV $21,001-$31,000) offers reduced subsidies. Green card covers all other citizens. Application is via Singpass or hardcopy form, with cards valid for two years.\

\f0\b CareShield Life
\f1\b0  provides long-term care insurance for severe disability (unable to perform 3+ of 6 ADLs). It's automatic at age 30 for those born 1980 or later, optional for earlier birth years. Base monthly payout is 
\f0\b $662 in 2025
\f1\b0  for life if severely disabled, with premiums payable from MediSave until age 67.\

\f0\b Seniors' Mobility and Enabling Fund
\f1\b0  covers assistive devices (walking sticks, wheelchairs, hearing aids, spectacles), home healthcare items (diapers, supplements), and transport subsidies for seniors with household monthly income per person \uc0\u8804 $2,000. Subsidies cover up to 90% of costs.\

\f0\b Referral pathway knowledge
\f1\b0  must include:\
Active Ageing Centres (214 locations) provide programs, befriending, information/referrals, community dining, and functional screening. Contact through AIC Hotline 1800-650-6060.\
Social Service Offices administer ComCare assistance and link to employment, family services. Located throughout Singapore; ComCare Hotline 1800-222-0000.\
Family Service Centres (50+ locations) provide casework, counselling, and support programs through social workers and counsellors.\

\f0\b Documentation requirements
\f1\b0  include recording visit date/time/duration, general appearance observations, screening scores, home environment notes, senior-raised concerns, changes from previous visits, actions taken, and follow-up needed.\

\f0\b Interactive content:
\f1\b0  A searchable reference tool showing scheme eligibility flowcharts, key phone numbers, and common senior questions with suggested responses. Include a quiz requiring learners to match senior scenarios with appropriate schemes.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

