\f0\b \cf0 Visit structure using BELIEF framework:
\f1\b0 \

\f0\b Break ice
\f1\b0  (5-10 minutes): Warm greeting in appropriate language/dialect, introduce yourself and purpose, show identification, ask permission to enter, make small talk about family/interests, find common ground.\

\f0\b Explore situation
\f1\b0  (10-15 minutes): Ask about health since last visit, daily routines, family support, any concerns. Observe home environment. Use open questions from MI training.\

\f0\b Listen with empathy
\f1\b0  (ongoing throughout): Apply active listening techniques, reflect feelings, allow silence, watch for non-verbal cues.\

\f0\b Inform to educate
\f1\b0  (10-15 minutes): Share relevant scheme information based on needs identified. Explain Healthier SG enrollment. Provide information about AAC activities. Use simple language; avoid jargon.\

\f0\b Evaluate and assure
\f1\b0  (5-10 minutes): Summarize key points. Confirm understanding. Address any remaining questions. Provide reassurance.\

\f0\b Follow-up
\f1\b0  (final minutes): Explain next steps. Leave contact information. Schedule any follow-up if needed. Thank them for their time.\

\f0\b Safety protocols for home visits
\f1\b0  include: positioning yourself near exits, being aware of surroundings, using non-threatening body language, listening to instincts (leave if feeling unsafe), having clear boundaries, knowing when to end visits.\

\f0\b Comprehensive scenario practice:
\f1\b0  A full 15-minute branching simulation featuring a senior with multiple needs\'97hearing loss, signs of isolation, confusion about medication management, eligibility for schemes they haven't claimed, and potential fall risk in the home. Learners must demonstrate communication adaptations, appropriate screening, scheme explanation, referral decisions, and documentation.\

\f0\b Final assessment:
\f1\b0  A cumulative quiz covering all modules (10-15 questions, 80% pass threshold) followed by an action planning prompt: "Based on this training, identify three specific things you will do in your first PHV to apply what you've learned."\
